Jun 18 2009 	The Holiday Inn Fisherman's Wharf is convenient to everything in San Francisco	The location was convenient and only a couple of blocks from the Wharf, depending on where one wanted to go along the Wharf area. To get to Pier 39, it did take more than two blocks walking, but it was interesting with street performers along the way, and lots of shops to shop in and restaurants to eat in. Tour buses pick passengers up in front of the hotel, and busses pass and stop one after the other all day and night along the three or so intersecting streets by the hotel. We were only a few blocks from Ghiradelli Square and the cable car turn-arounds. The hotel was nice and spotless inside. The rooms were totally spotless, had nice bedding with a light comforter sandwiched between two sheets, and lots of pillows. The TV was programmed to the hotel channel and it was hard to get to the other channels after we first turned it on daily. The towels were large and fluffy and the hotel hopes you will use them more than one day in order to conserve water. Shampoo, hand lotion, and two different soaps were provided, but no shower gel. There are large magnifying make-up mirrors in each bath, which was a real convenience. There is a restaurant/coffee shop off the hotel lobby, but it was very expensive. If you eat there--and it is very convenient--plan on spending 2-3 times above normal. On the downside, we were put at the end of a very, very long hallway and had to walk considerable distance to our room after having walked a great deal sightseeing. This was a real inconvenience and was a sore spot on the trip as we are seniors and don't have the stamina we once had. Don't rent a car unless you really need to as it costs $41 or more to park there overnight, every night. Public transportation is widely available everywhere around San Francisco, so one doesn't need a car unless you drive outside the city. We did have a great time while at the hotel for the 7 nights we were booked there. It was a home away from home, and other than the daily long walks down the hall to our room, and back to the ice and soft drink machines, and back down the hall again, we enjoyed the property and its location. We never did go to the pool or business center as we were always busy with other things, so can't review those amenities of the hotel. One last thought: if booking through an on-line travel website, be sure to CALL the hotel before you go and make sure your reservation is in their system. Ours was supposed to be all set up, yet they didn't have our reservation when we got there, and even though we'd emailed the hotel directly, we never got a response and just presumed we were all set up. Would we stay there again? Yes, if we ever have the luxury of returning to San Francisco--a great city with lots to do and see.	
