Jan 31 2009 	Loved the location - could not have been better	This is the closest hotel to all the action. Believe it or not it is also the cheapest at only $129. You can walk to all the attractions San Fransisco has to offer. fisherman's wharf, golden gate bridge, bay bridge, all the piers including pier 39. boats to Alcatraz., sea lions. the old chocolate factory and the trolley cars..Remember the web site says they charge $40 to park which works out to $46 because of all the taxes there. every place charges to park so if you want to save a small amount you can park at the wharf in a garage for $15 and walk back to the hotel or take the trolley ($1.50 for all day) only downside is this is a low rise so no view at all from the hotel windows if that is what you are looking for. You can do all you need to do there in a day and a half. so don't waist a whole week of your vacation here.	
Jan 28 2009	Fisherman's Wharf Holiday Inn notes	My daughter (22) and I just returned from a trip to San Francisco and the Fisherman's Wharf Holiday Inn. We found the location to be convenient to the sights we were interested in. We rode the cable car (nearby) and caught the city bus directly across the street. Buena Vista Cafe is a couple of blocks, easy walking distance. North Beach restaurants are a short bus ride away. The Wharf of course is walking distanceWe arrived on a Friday night (10:00 pm) and we asked the front desk attendant where we might eat, he told us everything was closed. Not true. He actually sent us the wrong direction. When you come out of the hotel, take a right and you will find a couple of bars/clubs, pizza and an In-N- Out Burger which is open very late.The Bellman and the Concierge were very helpful (just not on duty on Friday night). The hotel has absolutely no atmosphere (typical Holiday Inn) and no view, but the rooms are large and extremely clean and comfortable. We had planned to move to a more historic property with a view but decided we were comfortable. On the fifth floor is a business center with 3 computers and printers and internet access. We booked on Hotwire and got the room for under $100/night (taxes and fees included). All-in-all a very good deal.If you have a car, it is probably better to stay somewhere with free parking like the Columbus Motor Inn. We rented a car for the day from the Dollar counter in the Sheraton. Instead of keeping it overnight, we parked it in its space in the Sheraton garage and returned the keys the next morning. No need to pay parking.Be sure to eat at Mama's on Washington Square for breakfast and Trattoria Volare Caffe on Columbus for an Italian dinner or lunch.	
