Jan 10 2009 	Fair	We stayed at the Holiday Inn at the Wharf last year, arriving on Halloween and leaving on November 3rd. We found it to be fair without being outstanding, but not deserving of some of the criticism I’ve seen on this site. The hotel is situated a block or two back from the actual Wharf area, and it’s a short walk to both Wharf area restaurants and the Cable Car stop. We arrived by plane, so didn’t have to arrange parking. If you’re adventurous and not too heavily laden, the cheapest and probably most fun way to get there is on public transport. Get on the BART to Embarcadero, and then pick up a Trolley (not to be confused with the Trolley Busses) round to the Fishermans Wharf terminus which is literally round the block from the hotel. If you have suitcases, forget it and take a cab! Brits please note.There are Trolleys and Cable Cars in SF, both of which we would call trams. The Trolleys are actually what would be a tram in Britain, in fact there are a couple of old brit Trams there, as well as others from Italy, and other countries. They are quite cheap - $2 I think for pretty much the whole way. The Hotel is divided into two parts; there is a main building and an annex, which also contains a Denny’s restaurant. We stayed at the main building, which has the primary lobby, concierge, a small (overpriced) shop, and a restaurant and bar. All are adequately staffed and we didn’t have to wait too long to speak to anyone when we needed help. There are plenty of Bell hops if you need a hand with the bags, and on check in one was called for us and took us to our room with our bags. The hotel is occupies a whole block, but a small one about two football fields in size. However our room was at one end and the lobby at the other, so we had quite a walk each time. There was a staircase next to our room, but it came out in the car park with the only exit being at the lobby end again meaning we still had to walk 100 yards. The room was well appointed with the usual two queens, TV and shower. There was a reasonable space for clothing, although no wardrobe per se. There was a safe, iron and a laundry service. However like all Hotel laundry services it’s actually cheaper to buy new clothes than get them washed, so we didn’t bother. We were there on Halloween night, and there was admittedly a bit of noise from the revellers. At no point did we feel disturbed or particularly threatened by any of it though. Fisherman's Wharf is a busy area, and San Francisco a compact city. Noise is inevitable, but it didn't detract from our stay in any way.The Hotel has a pool (open and unheated) and fitness centre, remarkably like every other pool and fitness centre we encountered. Free towels and loungers and room key access only. It being November only us Brits were interested in the pool, although the fitness centre did have a few devotees. There’s no lifeguard, so kids need supervision, but it’s a perfectly adequate area, and on the one sunny day was a pleasant afternoons diversion.The Bar and restaurant in the Main lobby area were clean, if a little sparse. When we ate there the food was adequate and of course the kids ate free. They tend to eat only the kids menu, which is pretty cheap anyway, but it’s worth saving a buck or two if you can. Breakfast is also served there, and again they have a buffet, along with the usual fairly uninspiring choices. Denny’s in the annex was poor, and expensive. This seems to have happened to a lot of the fast food joints in the U.S. over the last few years. They used to be cheap and adequate, but both Denny’s in LA and SF we tried were not up to scratch at all. Even allowing for the fact the exchange rate was constantly turning against us while we were there, the prices were on the high side at Denny’s to the point it was worth going to ‘proper’ restaurants to get better quality food for not much more of your hard earned cash.All in all we found the Holiday Inn to be adequate although you might baulk at the room rate if you book directly. Because of a passport problem we had to stay another night and were quoted $170 per night for the room we’d previously occupied. We chose instead to stay at another hotel (nearer the airport) for about 1/3 of that price.I think if I was going back to the City, I might be inclined to try somewhere else, not because of any problems, but there was nothing about the place to draw us back.	
Jan 7 2009 	Great location cheap parking within walking distance	After reading a few reviews on this hotel, I booked it and hoped for the best. The front staff was very friendly and permitted us to check in early on Christmas Day. My sister who was traveling with us was also checked in early.The rooms were nice, not fancy but not subpar, they even had a pillow menu which we never used since we were fine with the pillows we had. The bathroom was tiny but served it's purpose and I would say that would be my only disappointment in the room.We did the buffet the 1st morning but it was alittle pricey. I recommend walking across the street to Cafe Peregonia I believe is the name, its a small place, big portions and nice service. I remember the green awning and that its next to a bicycle shop.Now for parking which is very expensive, DO NOT PARK at the hotel unless you want to part with $40 a day. We parked our cars overnight on the street, BUT we moved it at 7am to nearby parking garages such as the Anchorage Garage for an early bird special of $12 a day, don't bother moving your car from the garage until 7p when the meters do not need to be fed any coins. The cable cars, Ghiradelli square, Fishermans Wharf are all within 3 blks from the hotel and just head up Columbus for great Italian and if you venture further up you will come uopn Chinatown.	
