Mar 16 2007 	Disappointing for a Holiday Inn	We probably made a mistake at check in. We had booked a non smoking room. We were given a choice – a non smoking room in a separate Annex block, or an upgrade room in the hotel itself – albeit a smoking room. After an 11 hour flight and no sleep for nearly 24 hours I cannot always think too clearly; I picked the upgrade. The word ‘Annex’ conveys the impression of something tacked on and ‘upgrade’ of unexpected benefits and luxury. When we got to the room, I couldn’t help but think “if this is the upgrade, then I wonder what the standard rooms are like”. I wouldn’t go as far as to say it was awful, but it was certainly very tired and in desperate need of refurbishment. It also had a hint of that nasty odour caused by stale cigarette smoke which I suppose was not unexpected. In short, it was disappointing. If it wasn’t for the fact we were cross eyed with tiredness coupled with the knowledge we were only there for one night, I would probably have requested a different room. On the cleanliness front, I would describe it as reasonably clean but not spotlessly clean. With regard to the heating/air conditioning arrangements, there did not seem to be much variance between hot and cold on the rather ancient unit. Fortunately, neither was really necessary; we had excellent weather for January. On the positive side, there was complimentary internet access on the floor (part of the ‘upgrade’ package), as well as a decent sized fridge in the room. We found the staff to be helpful and pleasant, particularly the concierge. We didn’t eat in the hotel; breakfast seemed expensive for what it was, but there were a number of places just a few minutes walk away from the hotel that did breakfasts for just a few dollars. For dinner, I had done a little bit of research before we arrived. Seemed to me that while there were indeed loads of restaurants in the vicinity, none seemed to stand out as being particularly remarkable. So we picked out one in the Russian Hill district called Antica Trattoria on Polk Street (at Union). It is a ‘neighbourhood’ restaurant (ie frequented by locals) – always a good sign in my experience. It was excellent (you can look it up by tapping the name into Google). About a 10-12 minute walk from the hotel, up a steep hill – but it’s downhill on the way back! Cost us approx £30 a head with all drinks including a very pleasant bottle of Napa Valley Pinot Noir – a good meal for a fair price. After we got back to the hotel, we had a quick night cap in the bar. We found the barman to be helpful and knowledgeable.Noting some of the previous comments over the ‘tackiness’ of the area – it certainly was in places. It would be unfair to label the whole area in that way though. ‘Touristy’ it certainly is – and we knew that when we booked. Overall though we found the area to be quite pleasant with a relaxed atmosphere; the nearby Cannery certainly falls into that category. From that perspective, the hotel is very well located. I would only stay at this hotel again if I knew that the rooms had been refurbished. As it was, it was singularly unremarkable.	
Mar 6 2007	Good value for money	We booked an all in flight/hotel deal which was very cheap, being off season. Stayed in 2nd building but had large room with two queen sized beds and was quiet. There was a laundry room in our building and a business centre with internet access in main building which was very useful for checking in for return flight. Reception was helpful but could have done with more staff as often queues. Concierge very friendly and helpful for booking tours. Location was good, historic street car F just around block which takes you to Union Square. As seniors the transport cost us just 50 cents with transfers, amazing value. Some of restaurants on Fisherman`s Wharf seemed a bit tacky, recommend McCormick and Kuleto`s. Excellent sea food with wonderful views.	
