ancisco on business. Since my clients are walking distance to Fishermans Wharf, I always stay in that area even though it is obviously &quot;touristy&quot;. I've stayed at the Hyatt, the Best Western, and the Holiday Inn Express on previous visits. None are perfect, but all are better than the Holiday Inn. Since Holiday Inn's Priority Club seems to be the only frequent stayer program that actually lets you use the awards you've earned, I favor those hotels. On my next trip, I'll probably go back to the Holiday Inn Express, which is the same price as the Holiday Inn, but has more reliable hotel-wide wireless internet and a complimentary continental breakfast.	
Dec 13 2005	Location Location Location	Yes, this is a Holiday Inn, not the Hilton. (careful, there are several Holiday Inns in the area and many people got confused when checking in.)This was located on the corner of Columbus Ave and North Point Street. However, the four nights spent here were fine and a real value because of the AAA bed and breakfast rate ($123 Sun-Thur, $133 Fri and Sat) which included the cold continental breakfast($13.99 pp) and parking ($32 per day). This is a five story hotel located three blocks from the warf where all the tours are accessible. On the same block and next door you will find Holiday Inn Express, Marriott, Hyatt, and Hilton, all low rise hotels. One block closer to the warf is the Marriott Courtyard. Noise was certainly an issue, especially when we did not realize housekeeping cracked the window open and did not close it. I resorted to my earplugs brought from home to finally get some sleep. I imagine all rooms facing North Point Street in all hotels listed would be on the noisy side. In this hotel, odd numbered rooms face the street and even numbers are facing a wall (probably much more quiet). Mary, at reception, was great with offering to move us but we declined (unpacked already otherwise I would have done it). Our room was large with a couch in it. Other rooms offered a microwave and refrigerator but no couch. Other then the noise, this was the perfect location and met our needs fine.Two blocks away was Ghirardelli Square, shops and ice-cream. Across Columus Ave. was the Cannery, shops and restaurants.The city tour on Greyline (pier 43 1/2) was very informative. The wine tour with Greyline was great because of Ken, our driver. He knew a great deal and was so polite.30 minutes away is Muir Woods. The redwoods were interesting to see and the trails are easy for anyone to enjoy.Of course Alcatraz can't be missed. Boats on the Blue and Gold line leave multiple times in a day from Pier 41. I recommend buying tickets in advance (for us only one day because it was off season) either by phone or in person.Pier 39 is full of restaurants but don't miss the experience of buying a crab from the street vendors for a real San Francisco experience to remember.	
