Jul 17 2005	Happy at the Holiday Inn	First off - if you are driving in to the SF area - stop off at any rest stop and grab one of those hotel coupons book (we used the &quot;Traveler&quot;). With our coupon we really saved a lot of money for our 6 night stay. We were quoted between $219-$250 and wound up getting a room for $145 on Fri and Sat and $129 for week day nights. Being right in the heart of the Fisherman's Wharf area for this amount of money was truly a bargain! We also got an upgrade from a standard room to a room on the &quot;business level&quot; which is on the 5th floor. Never hurts to ask for an upgrade and we didn't have to pay any additional fees.I was informed that this hotel had been recently renovated to the tune of several million dollars. Not sure if I buy that or not but the room was extremely clean with the following ammenities: a key safe, king size bed, chair w/ ottoman, desk, iron and ironing board, roomy bathroom, nice sopas, shampoos, etc., hairdryer, and black-out drapes (a must!). Also, wireless internet access is free! Our particular room (room 560) didn't have a closet or an armoire so we had to use a valet on wheels to hang our clothes. Strange but it worked and there was plenty of room to put it against the wall without it getting in the way. Our room faced &quot;The Cannery&quot; and had a view of Alcatraz. You could see a little bit of the Pacific Ocean but I would not call it an &quot;ocean view&quot;. Basically your view from our particular room on the 5th floor was the Marriot Hotel! But overall I wasn't unhappy with what I saw outside the window. I don't think this view would be as good on any of the other floors (there are only 5). I also agree with another reviewer regarding the noise level from the street. It was noisy with the &quot;Dirty Martini&quot; bar across the street and cars/bikes passing by but honestly if you can get a piece of pizza 'til 2:00 in the morning across the street at &quot;Fisherman's Pizza&quot; - can you really complain??? And after all, you're in a big city! If you are looking for quiet, head south on Road 1 to the Big Sur area! The staff were extremely accomodating from the bell hop to the concierge. If you plan to stay in the city for at least 3 days pick up a &quot;Muni Pass&quot; which will allow you to jump on a bus anywhere in the city... it's really worth it. The hotel lists an outdoor heated pool and a fitness facility. The pool is small but we didn't really come here to swim anyway and the fitness facility consists of 2 treadmills, 2 ellipticals, and a bike - there is also a television. I don't think I would call it a &quot;fitness facility&quot; as it's more a &quot;cardio room!&quot; Again, this didn't concern me as I wasn't here to train... and you get plenty of cardio walking around anyway.I liked this hotel, would recommend it and would return. Oh, one more thing, they charge you $30.00 per day to park your car here. But that's pretty much status quo here. If you are flying in - you might want to consider not renting a vehicle and using mass transit. It's hard getting around by car and you have to pay to park everywhere.Good luck and Happy Traveling!Debbie from Jupiter	
Jul 4 2005	Great Location - right in the heart of things	This hotel does have an excellent location for exploring the Wharf, catching a cable car etc and has a number of very good restaraunts close by. It can only be a couple of hundred metres to the waterfront. The staff were very friendly and helpful. The rooms were average HI but nothing that I could complain about - generally the usual Holiday Inn standard that you can trust. The pool is quite small but many people probably wont spend much time in the pool in San Fran anyway. Although its relatvely expensive for a Holiday Inn it a very reasonably priced hotel in terms of San Frnasisco. It's right next to the Holiday Inn Express and the Hilton. There is a business centre with free internet access which is nice. There is a restaraunt but we never ate there.Be very careful if buying any camera/ video equipment near the Wharf - it pays to be a well informed buyer. They can smell an opportunity to make a fast 100 + bucks!If going back to SF then I probably would go back to this Hotel. I have stayed at the Civic Centre area in SF on a previous visit but I would say don't do it. There is no comparison in terms of location. The Wharf wins hands down every time. The Civic Centre area is a soup kitchen, blanket dispensing haven for SF's homeless - which is good for them but not what most people will want to experience daily on a trip to California. You could no doubt pay more and get a more upmarket hotel but I doubt the location would be any better any where around the wharf. A good deal all round. Well done Holiday Inn.	
